ks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Corbucion II was born about 1085, in Studley, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir William FitzCorbucion I, was 41 and his mother, Mrs William FitzCorbucion, was 37. He had at least 2 sons. He died in Chillington Hall, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1085–":"umbes 1085–Surnud","1085–Male":"1085–Surnud","1115–1166":"1115–1166","–1170":"–1170","1045–1089":"1045–1089","1050–Female":"1050–Surnud","Abt 1085":"umbes 1085","1115":"1115","1089":"1089","1045":"1045","1166":"1166","1085":"1085","1050":"1050","1170":"1170","Chillington Hall, Wolverhampton, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Chillington Hall, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Studley, Stratford-on-Avon, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom":"Studley, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1085–":"noin 1085–Kuollut","1085–Male":"1085–Kuollut","1115–1166":"1115–1166","–1170":"–1170","1045–1089":"1045–1089","1050–Female":"1050–Kuollut","Abt 1085":"noin 1085","1115":"1115","1089":"1089","1045":"1045","1166":"1166","1085":"1085","1050":"1050","1170":"1170","Chillington Hall, Wolverhampton, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Chillington Hall, Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Studley, Stratford-on-Avon, Warwickshire, England, 